snapshot.s:
Business Case for 
“Computer Science Day”

1.0  Introduction/ Background
 
 Informatics 151 Team SCAR is interested in increasing awareness and excitement in high school students entering college about related computer science majors and degrees.  While computer science as a field has become increasingly more popular as new technologies and opportunities become available and computing becomes a part of our daily lives, there still remains a stereotype surrounding the study of computers that may be unattractive or “uncool” for kids.  We believe that by creating more computer science introductory events oriented around topics that kids enjoy, we may be able to accelerate the growth of the computer science population, specifically for UC Irvine.
 
2.0 Business Objective
 
 Team SCAR’s goals for this project include increasing awareness and excitement about the computer science field for high school students and to increase the number of incoming freshmen at UC Irvine with a declared major in the computer science field.  A secondary goal for this project is to also specifically target female high school students in an attempt to create a more equal ratio between men and women in the historically male population of the computer science majors.  We propose a “Computer Science Day” event at UC Irvine to satisfy these goals.  The event focus would be to create links between exciting new industry opportunities in fields that kids are interested in and computer science degrees, emphasizing female involvement in computer science with well known female figures as guest speakers, and increasing the computer-confidence of students through participation in games and activities.  We believe an event such as this will satisfy our goals and may even become actualized given the amount of planning and work accomplished.
 
3.0 Current Situation and Problem/Opportunity Statement
 
 Currently, Information and Computer Science degrees at UCI make up the lowest portion of degrees given out.  In a University of California, Irvine graduation profile for Fall 2009, only 3% of graduates were graduating with a degree in a computer science related major.  This will inevitably improve slightly over the course of the next few years, especially with the introduction of the popular game science major.  However, since this is the first year the game science major has been available, there is opportunity to capitalize on the buzz and hype surrounding it to draw students into all majors within the computer science field.  After attending a few ICS events targeted at recruiting new freshmen with a declared computer science degree, it is obvious that there is room for improvement.  Women make up only a small percentage of attendees to current events and presentations seem quite standard.  We have the opportunity to be unique and to begin a paradigm shift from kids commonly viewing computer science as a “nerdy” degree to something that is fun, cool, and an interesting choice for both men and women.
 
4.0 Critical Assumption and Constraints
 The following are assumptions and constraints that SCAR will assume.  We are assuming that we will be able to recruit both male and female high school students.  On the same token we are also assuming some of the attendees already have a keen interest, while others have not yet developed an interest.  We are also realistic and aware that the current statistic of people graduating with a computer science major of 3% will not raise drastically from this single fair.  And lastly, we are assuming that there will be room availability for the week of March 13 to sign out the room. 

5.0 Analysis of Options and Recommendation
 
There are three options for addressing this opportunity:

Forgo this project and think of a project with a more probable and greater return
Hire a seasoned event planner from the UCI ICS staff to put on the event with our vision in mind.
Plan and execute the event ourselves
 
Based on the constraints and requirements of the informatics 151 course, the goals of our stakeholders (including Professor Olson), and the goals of team SCAR, we believe option 3 to be the best option.
6.0 Preliminary Project Requirements
There are a number of requirements that must be completed.  These are as follows:

1. Advertisements.  These consist of a number of different forms.  Fliers must be made and hung up around UCI and local high schools, and given out to high school students and their parents.  In order to accomplish this, a form listing the names and contact information of all the high schools in the area must be made.

2. Event schedule.  In order to make the event schedule, many UCI professors and administrators must first be contacted.  We will need to determine who is willing to speak at the event.  For each speaker, a number of items must be decided.  These consist of how long the speaker will present for, a general overview of what they will be presenting, whether the presentation would be aimed at parents, students, or both, and the time and location of the presentation.  All of this information will be combined into one document that is the event schedule.  

3. Event information document.  This document will detail the aesthetic features of the fair.  Examples of these are a map of the school pointing to where each of the lectures will be and information about where to enter and where to park.

4. Sample event presentation.  A powerpoint presentation that will be used by one of the presenters at the event.  Each presentation is meant to focus around one key idea or concept that will either spark interest in the fields of logic and programming in high school students, or convince parents that Computer Science is a worthwhile field for their children to study.

5.  “Hook” presentation.  This powerpoint presentation will be shown to high school students at their school to interest them in coming to the event at UCI.  It is meant to entice students into wanting to learn more about programming and Computer Science and “hook” them into bringing themselves and their parents to the Computer Science Day. 
 
7.0 Budget Estimate and Financial Analysis
 
 The preliminary estimate of the cost of this event would equal the amount of paper printouts, and anything we provide during the event, such as refreshments. Paper printouts would include fliers that would be sent out to certain high schools, event schedules, and an overall program that would be needed to be passed out to anyone attending the event. Paper copies are usually around $.05-$0.10 per copy, and we would need around 300 copies, which would cost anywhere around $45-$90. A range of $150-$200 would be used on snacks and refreshments for the event. Overall, it is a free event for any attendees, which include high school students and their parents, but we may need to reimburse them for parking if we cannot reserve a parking structure for the attendees. The personnel, which includes, but is not limited to, Team SCAR, current ICS students, guest speakers, and various computer science professors would be volunteering to administrate the event or lecture during the event unpaid. Reserving rooms for use in the Donald Bren Hall is also free of charge.
 
(Maybe?)
(If we were to implement a raffle into the event, then we would need to also need to suggest three items to purchase, for first, second, and third place prizes, with the tickets costing a fair amount (about a dollar for two, or so) so that we could earn the money back from the cost of the prizes. Another thing we could do is provide t-shirts for the first 100 students who show up.)
 
8.0 Schedule Estimate
 There are several schedules that must be kept in mind.  Estimation for overall completion is ten weeks; there is no flexibility for projection completion.  The procurement process will take four weeks and the recruiting process will take nine weeks.  The fair will be held for one day. 
 
9.0 Potential Risks
 Potential risks are definitely present in planning the event.  The most obvious risk is investing time/money and not realizing the benefits.  However, this is more an effect of the most true and feared potential risk: student lack of interest.  SCAR also faces the possibility of the fair being canceled if a room in Bren Hall is not reserved within four weeks.  If we are able to launch the event successfully, we still continue to run the risk of lack of diversity if the fair continues to attract predominantly males.   
 
10.0 Exhibits
Exhibit A: Financial Analysis
 


Forgo this project and think of a project with a more probable and greater return
Hire a seasoned event planner from the UCI ICS staff to put on the event with our vision in mind.

5.  “Hook” presentation.  This powerpoint presentation will be shown to high school students at their school to interest them in coming to the event at UCI. 7.0 Budget Estimate and Financial Analysis
 
 The preliminary estimate of the cost of this event would equal the amount of paper printouts, anything we provide for or during the event, such as refreshments, parking reservations for the event, and also any prizes/free gifts for attendees. Paper printouts would include fliers that would be sent out to certain high schools, event schedules, and an overall program that would be needed to be passed out to anyone attending the event. Paper copies are usually around $.05-$0.10 per copy, and we would need around 500 copies, which would cost anywhere around $75-$150. About $300 would be used on snacks and refreshments for the event. This would be considered a free event for any attendees, which include high school students and their parents. The personnel, which includes, but is not limited to, Team SCAR, current ICS students, guest speakers, and various computer science professors would be volunteering to administrate the event or lecture during the event unpaid. Reserving rooms for use in the Donald Bren Hall is also free of charge.
 Parking spots in the Anteater Parking Lot would need to be reserved for attendees, which would cost $8 per space, which attendees would need to pay for themselves, $16/hr for an employee to watch over the spaces, and a $50 barricade fee, and we would need to reserve about 300-500 spaces.
 We would also like to implement a raffle into the event, for which the first, second, and third place prizes could be gift cards or prizes worth $50, $25, and $10 respectively, with the ticket price being $1 per 2 tickets. Another thing we want to give away to the first 50 students who arrive are UCI Bren: ICS t-shirts, which when bought in bulk can cost about $1 per shirt, which totals to $135 for all of the prizes/giveaways for this event.  There is also the possibility of donated raffle items.  It is not uncommon for companies like Microsoft or Google to give away merchandise, especially if we give them the opportunity to discuss what opportunities computer science majors have at their companies.
 
8.0 Schedule Estimate

 There are several schedules that must be kept in mind.  Estimation for overall completion is ten weeks; there is no flexibility for projection completion.  The procurement process will take four weeks and the recruiting process will take nine weeks.  The fair will be held for one day. 
 
9.0 Potential Risks

 Potential risks are definitely present in planning the event.  The most obvious risk is investing time/money and not realizing the benefits.  However, this is more an effect of the most true and feared potential risk: student lack of interest.  SCAR also faces the possibility of the fair being canceled if a room in Bren Hall is not reserved within four weeks.  If we are able to launch the event successfully, we still continue to run the risk of lack of diversity if the fair continues to attract predominantly males.

And of course we will be constrained by our budget which has yet to be finalized (since we may be able to receive funding from the ICS department).

5.0 Analysis of Options and Recommendation
 
There are three options for addressing this opportunity:

Forgo this project and think of a project with a more probable and greater return
Hire a seasoned event planner from the UCI ICS staff to put on the event with our vision in mind.
Plan and execute the event ourselves
 
Based on the constraints and requirements of the informatics 151 course, the goals of our stakeholders (including Professor Olson), and the goals of team SCAR, we believe option 3 to be the best option.
6.0 Preliminary Project Requirements

There are a number of requirements that must be completed.  These are as follows:

1. Advertisements.  These consist of a number of different forms.  Fliers must be made and hung up around UCI and local high schools, and given out to high school students and their parents.  In order to accomplish this, a form listing the names and contact information of all the high schools in the area must be made.

2. Event schedule.  In order to make the event schedule, many UCI professors and administrators must first be contacted.  We will need to determine who is willing to speak at the event.  For each speaker, a number of items must be decided.  These consist of how long the speaker will present for, a general overview of what they will be presenting, whether the presentation would be aimed at parents, students, or both, and the time and location of the presentation.  All of this information will be combined into one document that is the event schedule.  

3. Event information document.  This document will detail the aesthetic features of the fair.  Examples of these are a map of the school pointing to where each of the lectures will be and information about where to enter and where to park.

4. Sample event presentation.  A powerpoint presentation that will be used by one of the presenters at the event.  Each presentation is meant to focus around one key idea or concept that will either spark interest in the fields of logic and programming in high school students, or convince parents that Computer Science is a worthwhile field for their children to study.

5.  “Hook” presentation.  This powerpoint presentation will be shown to high school students at their school to interest them in coming to the event at UCI.  It is meant to entice students into wanting to learn more about programming and Computer Science and “hook” them into bringing themselves and their parents to the Computer Science Day. 
 
7.0 Budget Estimate and Financial Analysis
 
 The preliminary estimate of the cost of this event would equal the amount of paper printouts, anything we provide for or during the event, such as refreshments, parking reservations for the event, and also any prizes/free gifts for attendees. Paper printouts would include fliers that would be sent out to certain high schools, event schedules, and an overall program that would be needed to be passed out to anyone attending the event. Paper copies are usually around $.05-$0.10 per copy, and we would need around 500 copies, which would cost anywhere around $75-$150. About $300 would be used on snacks and refreshments for the event. This would be considered a free event for any attendees, which include high school students and their parents. The personnel, which includes, but is not limited to, Team SCAR, current ICS students, guest speakers, and various computer science professors would be volunteering to administrate the event or lecture during the event unpaid. Reserving rooms for use in the Donald Bren Hall is also free of charge.
 Parking spots in the Anteater Parking Lot would need to be reserved for attendees, which would cost $8 per space, which attendees would need to pay for themselves, $16/hr for an employee to watch over the spaces, and a $50 barricade fee, and we would need to reserve about 300-500 spaces.
 We would also like to implement a raffle into the event, for which the first, second, and third place prizes could be gift cards or prizes worth $50, $25, and $10 respectively, with the ticket price being $1 per 2 tickets. Another thing we want to give away to the first 50 students who arrive are UCI Bren: ICS t-shirts, which when bought in bulk can cost about $1 per shirt, which totals to $135 for all of the prizes/giveaways for this event.  There is also the possibility of donated raffle items.  It is not uncommon for companies like Microsoft or Google to give away merchandise, especially if we give them the opportunity to discuss what opportunities computer science majors have at their companies.
 
8.0 Schedule Estimate

 There are several schedules that must be kept in mind.  Estimation for overall completion is ten weeks; there is no flexibility for projection completion.  The procurement process will take four weeks and the recruiting process will take nine weeks.  The fair will be held for one day. 
 
9.0 Potential Risks

 Potential risks are definitely present in planning the event.  The most obvious risk is investing time/money and not realizing the benefits.  However, this is more an effect of the most true and feared potential risk: student lack of interest.  SCAR also faces the possibility of the fair being canceled if a room in Bren Hall is not reserved within four weeks.  If we are able to launch the event successfully, we still continue to run the risk of lack of diversity if the fair continues to attract predominantly males.
